For the convenience, we are going to merge the training set and the testing set together. Then, they will be separated after the data process which converting the distinct data by the categorization or by the dummy variables. Following the conversion, they will also be rescaled with the values between 0 and 1 and will be considered as the probabilities.

In [6]:
total_data = train_data.append(test_data)
# to unify the column income_bracket
total_data["income_bracket"] = total_data["income_bracket"].str.replace(".", "")

Categorization¶

Some features are labeled in text, and we convert them into integer numbers to distinguish the differences. For example, the education of employee are Assoc-acdm, Some-college, and so on, and they are distincted by 0, 1, 2, ...

In [7]:
indiced_single_feature_data = pd.DataFrame(total_data.copy())
for col in ["workclass", "education", "marital_status", "occupation", "relationship", "race", "gender", "native_country", "income_bracket"]:
    indiced_single_feature_data.loc[:, col] = index_single_feature(indiced_single_feature_data[col].values)[0]

Next, we have to rescale each features to prevent the bias. More specifically, mean and variation of fnlwgt are huge, and squeeze other factors. Therefore, all features are rescaled between 0 and 1 to uniform factors, and that means weights of all features are equal.

In [9]:
indiced_single_feature_data = indiced_single_feature_data.apply(lambda x: (x - x.min()) / (x.max() - x.min()))
indiced_single_features = indiced_single_feature_data.iloc[:16281,:-1].values
indiced_single_labels = indiced_single_feature_data.iloc[:16281,-1].values
indiced_single_features_test = indiced_single_feature_data.iloc[16281:,:-1].values
indiced_single_labels_test = indiced_single_feature_data.iloc[16281:,-1].values

Finally, training data is put into a single neuron with multi-input and single output. It is not sure if a single output is able to classify those with multi-input or not, although it is continous between 0 and 1, and there must be the potential.

In [11]:
indiced_single_features_estimator = [
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=50),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=100),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=200),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=400),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000)
]

First, we study the relation between the convergence and the batch size, and the results are shown below. It is found that the larger the batch is, the smaller the fluctuation is. Usually, it is necessary to fit model with the sufficient large samples, and then the result would be approaching to the accurate target. In other words, once the batch is too small, there is a challenge to shot on the target like the blue line which does not converge to the target.

In [12]:
data = [go.Scatter(x=np.arange(1000),
                   y=np.array(indiced_single_features_estimator[0].loss),
                   mode="lines",
                   name="batch_size: 50"),
        go.Scatter(x=np.arange(1000),
                   y=np.array(indiced_single_features_estimator[1].loss),
                   mode="lines",
                   name="batch_size: 100"),
        go.Scatter(x=np.arange(1000),
                   y=np.array(indiced_single_features_estimator[2].loss),
                   mode="lines",
                   name="batch_size: 200"),
        go.Scatter(x=np.arange(1000),
                   y=np.array(indiced_single_features_estimator[3].loss),
                   mode="lines",
                   name="batch_size: 400"),
        go.Scatter(x=np.arange(1000),
                   y=np.array(indiced_single_features_estimator[4].loss),
                   mode="lines",
                   name="batch_size: 1000")]
layout = go.Layout(
    title='Learning Rate: 1e-3',
    xaxis=dict(
        title='iteration steps',
    ),
    yaxis=dict(
        title='negative cross entropy'
    )
)
fig = go.Figure(data=data, layout=layout)
iplot(fig)
In [13]:
indiced_single_features_estimator = [
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-1)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-2)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=5e-2)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-3)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000),
    ClassifierNN(indiced_single_features, indiced_single_labels)\
        .optimize(learning_rate=1e-4)\
        .estimate(batch_size=1000)
]

Moreover, we able to calibrate convergent rate by altering learning rate, and the larger learning rate provides the fast convergence. Additionally, it is observed that the center of orange line is different to the blue line and the green line, and the value of orange line is larger. This indicates the minimum conducted by Adam optimization does not guarantee it is the global minimum. If the lerning rate is too large like the blue line, the result does not convergent monotonically either.

In [15]:
predicted_label = indiced_single_features_estimator[1].predict(indiced_single_features_test)
predicted_label = np.where(np.array(predicted_label) > 0.5, 1, 0)
accuracy = 1.0 - np.linalg.norm((predicted_label[0,:,0] - indiced_single_labels_test) / indiced_single_labels_test.shape[0])

Finally, we adopt the distance to measure the accuracy, and the result is rather amazing the value 99.76%. Probably, this problem is not frustrated enough to exhibit superiority of the deep learning and a single neuron is able to classify the income with the corresponding features excellently.

Dummy Variables¶

Now, categories are labeled by dummy variables rather than indices. Probably, it would provide more information for us to fit the model, and we are able to obtain more accurate results.

In [17]:
dummy_feature_data = pd.DataFrame(total_data.copy())
for col in ["workclass", "education", "marital_status", "occupation", "relationship", "race", "gender", "native_country", "income_bracket"]:
    dummy_col = dummy_feature_data[col]
    dummy_feature_data = pd.concat(
        [dummy_feature_data.drop(col, axis=1), pd.get_dummies(dummy_col)],
        axis=1)

In [23]:
predict_labels = dummy_features_estimator[1].predict(dummy_features_test)
accuracy = 1.0 - np.linalg.norm(0.5 * (dummy_labels_test - np.where(predict_labels[0] > 0, 1, 0)) / dummy_labels_test.shape[0])

High accurate result is obtained again. Probably, the problem is not so complicated to distinguish these two methods. However, it is believed it is simpler to pick labels as binaries, and we are able to make the decision by choosing the argument maximum. In other words, each label occupies different dimensions such that it is recognized by checking the state is filled or not rather confirming level of values.
